            <div type="edition">
                <ab><lb n="1"/> <persName><name key="Ζεῦξις">Ζεῦξις</name></persName>
                  <lb n="2"/> ἐπόησεν.
                    
                
                
            </ab></div>
            
            <div type="translation">
            <p>Zeuxis made (this).</p></div>

            <div type="commentary">
                <p>A fragmentary life-size portrait of a man seating at an easy posture. The head
                    and arms were made separately and attached to statue; both are now missing. The
                    costume and composition mark the man as a mortal, not a god. The existence of
                    several drilling holes in the upper part of the right arm suggests that the man
                    was holding an instrument, plausibly an instrument (a lyre or cithara) that
                    would identify him as a poet. Robinson (1910) identified the craftmanship with
                    Greek, offering to date the sculpture to the 3-2 c. BCE. Richter (1954) suggests
                    to date it to the 1 c. BCE based on the form of the letter ζ. The sculpturer
                    signed his name Zeuxis. Nothing else is known of him. The orthography shows a
                    loss of the diphthong οι (ἐπόησεν for ἐποίησεν).</p></div>
            
